Compiling the Main.java file with javac yields the following error message:
mnt/ssd/home/tgierke/luna_develop_workspace/jinvaders/src/main/java/de/codesourcery/jinvaders/Main.java:[111,25] cannot find symbol symbol: method removeEntity(de.codesourcery.jinvaders.entity.Entity)
I was refactoring some code so I moved the anonymous ITickListener instance that contains the offending line to the outer-most scope while the removeEntity() method remained a static method on some nested static class - this broke the Eclipse compilation.

At first glance this seems to be resulting from the fact that while resolving lambda expression, we are using a new silent error reporting policy, which is resulting in the bad method being allowed to code generation. Need to see what is the right way to handle this.

The reduced repro nicely shows the culprit:
While resolving the lambda we switch to silent error reporting policy, fine.
This triggers resolving of the field 'tickContext', fine.
Resolving of the field triggers resolving of the anonymous class in its initializer, well ...
Resolving the anonymous class needs to report an error, BUT we are still in silent mode.
Ergo: problem is that the silent mode can escape to locations where error reporting must be back to normal.
I added a simple suspend/resume pair to ProblemHandler, to handle this. For good measure I made these methods safe for nesting in any fashion.
Remaining problem: the trigger for crossing the boarder is FieldBinding.constant(), BUT this method doesn't have enough context to trigger the suspend/resume.
To fix this I added a new constant(Scope) method, which can fetch the problemReporter and perform the suspend/resume on this instance, fine.
Unfortunately, there are many locations invoking constant(). I changed a bunch of these call sites to using the new method passing a scope. Still, for full safety s.o. might still want to check the remaining callers of VariableBinding#constant() and FieldBinding#constant(), if any could occur in the call graph of LambdaExpression#cachedResolvedCopy().
See https://git.eclipse.org/r/40657 "Hudson, are you home???"
As an alternative, I'm investigating to move the trigger to a place like SingleNameReference.checkFieldAccess() where we still have the scope. This would just have to respect the different shapes of references to a field ...

(In reply to Stephan Herrmann from comment #6) > See https://git.eclipse.org/r/40657 > "Hudson, are you home???"
PW brought "him" back to life, great.
> As an alternative, I'm investigating to move the trigger to a place like > SingleNameReference.checkFieldAccess() where we still have the scope. This > would just have to respect the different shapes of references to a field ...
Hm, I'm no longer convinced this would simplify anything. We'd still have to reason what call chains could possibly trigger the resolving done inside FieldBinding.constant(). Better to keep the guard next to where it happens.
Tests signal OK, I'm just holding back the change to not interfere with the M5 respin later tonight.
Verified for 4.5 M6 with build I20150316-2000
